  "body": "For example, in this page: https://docs.perl6.org/language/exceptions\r\n\r\nCurrent example for \"Catching exceptions\" is:\r\n```\r\ndie X::IO::DoesNotExist.new(:path(\"foo/bar\"), :trying(\"zombie copy\"));\r\n \r\nCATCH {\r\n    when X::IO { say \"some kind of IO exception was caught!\" }\r\n}\r\n \r\n# RESULT: «some kind of IO exception was caught!» \r\n```\r\n\r\nBut I think the following is better than the former one:\r\n```\r\ndie X::IO::DoesNotExist.new(:path(\"foo/bar\"), :trying(\"zombie copy\"));\r\n \r\nCATCH {\r\n    when X::IO { $*ERR.say: \"some kind of IO exception was caught!\" }\r\n}\r\n \r\n# RESULT: «some kind of IO exception was caught!» \r\n```\r\n\r\nAre there any reasons to use STDOUT instead of STDERR?",
